                {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": "<p>At the end of the year 2014 the Dutch government has started a dialogue about the content of the educational curriculum of primary and secondary education in the Netherlands.</p>\n<p>The project was named \"Onderwijs 2032\" (\"Education 2032\").The project focuses on the kind of knowledge and skills students need to succeed in a 2032 society. Besides the focus on <em>what</em> skills should be taught it also seems of great importance to explore <em>how</em> these skills and knowledge should be taught.</p>\n<p>According to Trilling and Fadel (2009) the expectations and desires of individuals aged between eleven to thirty-one are clearly different from those of their parents. The expectations of these individuals, our students, present new sets of demands on our education systems. A one-size-fits-all model doesn't seem to work (anymore). New ways to make learning interactive, personalized, collaborative, creative, and innovative are therefore necessary to keep our current and future students actively learning in schools everywhere around the world. </p>\n"
                }
